acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Acquired primarily through gift from Stephen Vincent Benét, Rosemary Benét, and the estate of Rosemary Benét, 1942-1966.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The materials are open for research.
Boxes 138-143: Restricted fragile material. Reference surrogates have been substituted in the main files. For further information consult the appropriate curator.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary Benét papers is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary Benét Papers. Yale Collection of American Literature, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary Benét Papers contains material acquired by the library with gifts from Stephen Vincent Benét, Rosemary Benét, and the estate of Rosemary Benét from 1942 through 1966. Manuscript material formerly classified as Za Benet and Uncat Za Ms 158, as well as printed ephemera that had been cataloged separately, was brought together and re-processed during 2016-2017.
Former call numbers: Za Benet, Uncat Za Ms 158, Za B435 +1, Za B436 +1, Za B436 +2, Za B436 +3, and Za B436 +S2.

bioghist.head: Stephen Vincent Benét (1898-1943) and Rosemary Benét (1900-1962)
bioghist.p: Stephen Vincent Benét was a well known and widely read author in the United States during the 1930s and 1940s. After the success of his long poem, John Brown's Body (1928), for which he was awarded a Pulitzer Prize in 1929, he regularly published poems, short stories, and other work in popular magazines such as The Atlantic Monthly , The New Yorker , and The Saturday Evening Post . His short story, "The Devil and Daniel Webster" (1936) was awarded the O. Henry Memorial Award in 1937. In addition to poetry and short stories, he is the author of novels, book reviews, essays, radio and stage plays, screenplays, and speeches.

Rosemary Benét, born Rosemary Carr, is the author of poems, book reviews, essays, and short stories. She and her husband co-authored A Book of Americans (1933), a book of poems for children about prominent figures in American history.

Bibliographic, biographical, and critical studies on Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét include books by Mary Dearing Lewis (1952), Charles A. Fenton (1958), David Garret Izzo and Lincoln Konkle (2003), and Evelyn Helmick Hively (2011). Summary information is also available in the standard print and online biographical resources.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary Benét papers consist of correspondence, manuscripts, printed material, and personal and family papers documenting the life and work of American authors Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary Benét. The collection spans the years 1829 to 1962, with the bulk of the collection dating from roughly 1910 to 1943.
Collection material is chiefly in English; with some material in French, German, Polish, and Swedish.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into six series: I. Correspondence, 1887-1962. II. Family Correspondence, 1829-1962. III. Writings, 1870-1962. IV. Printed Appearances of Writings by Stephen Vincent Benét, 1916-1958. V. Printed Material, 1836-1962. VI. Personal Papers, 1843-1962.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Material by or relating to Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét acquired by the library from other Benét family sources can be located in the Benét Family Papers (YCAL MSS 1107). Material by or relating to Stephen Vincent Benét acquired by the library from non-family sources is located in the Benét Family Collection (YCAL MSS 1108). Additional material by or relating to Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét can also be found in the William Rose Benét Papers (YCAL MSS 1100).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into two subseries: General Correspondence and Third Party Correspondence. General Correspondence is arranged alphabetically by correspondent and chronologically within files. Third Party Correspondence is arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series I. General Correspondence consists chiefly of single letters and small groups of incoming personal and professional correspondence to Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary (Carr) Benét. There are letters from many English-language authors and literary critics of the first half of the twentieth century, as well as from friends, publishers, editors of journals and newspapers, literary, cultural, and civic organizations, academic institutions, and federal agencies. Larger files can be found for authors George Abbe, Paul Engle, and Robert Nathan, for Stephen Vincent Benét's biographer, Charles A. Fenton, the literary agency Brandt & Brandt, publishers Doubleday, Doran & Company and Farrar & Rinehart, and the Council for Democracy, a propaganda outlet for which Benét wrote radio scripts during Word War II. Such files also exist for fellow alumni of Yale College, including John Franklin Carter and Robert E. McClure, and expats with whom Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét socialized while living in Paris in the 1920s. These couples include Philip and Ellen (Semple) Barry, Douglas and Emily Moore, and Richard and Alice Lee Myers. Other correspondents include Hiram Bingham, Norman Cousins, Wilbur L. Cross, John Dos Passos, Arthur Davison Ficke, John Gould Fletcher, Sinclair Lewis, Archibald MacLeish, Kenneth Patchen, Beatrix Potter, Muriel Rukeyser, Carl Sandburg, and Thornton Wilder.

Stephen Vincent Benét died March 13, 1943, and Rosemary Benét died August 18, 1962. Correspondence marked from 1944 forward in the finding aid, or reflected in a date range that ends 1944 or later, clearly indicates the presence of correspondence to Rosemary Benét. Otherwise, individual letters within mixed files and files consisting exclusively of letters to Rosemary Benét are not indicated.

The Third Party Correspondence subseries consists of the loose third party correspondence in the series. Most likely these letters came into the Benét's possession as enclosures and, over time, were separated from the original letters.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into two subseries: General Correspondence and Other Family Letters. General Correspondence is arranged alphabetically first by correspondent (sender), then by recipient. The first correspondent (sender), for example, is Barton, Alexander, followed by Baxter, Lora. Letters are arranged chonologically within files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II. Family Correspondence consists chiefly of letters between members of the Benét, Carr, and Rose families. There are large files of original correspondence from Stephen Vincent to his mother, Frances Rose Benét, and to his wife Rosemary, and from Rosemary to Stephen Vincent. Letters to and from in-laws are also found here, including Kathleen and Charles Gilman Norris and Elinor Wylie. The Other Family Letters subseries includes third-party letters from non-family members.
Letters to Stephen Vincent Benét from Andrew Jones, a cousin, are located in Series I. Correspondence, General Correspondence, Boxes 15-16, folders 624-638.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into five subseries: Writings of Stephen Vincent Benét, Adaptations of Work by Stephen Vincent Benét, Writings of Rosemary Benét, Adaptations of Work by Rosemary Benét, and Writings of Others.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series III. Writings includes manuscript writings of Stephen Vincent Benét, manuscript and printed works by Rosemary Benét, adaptations of work by Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét, and writings by others. Printed versions of writings by Stephen Vincent Benét are filed in Series IV.

The manuscripts of Stephen Vincent Benét consist chiefly of drafts and proofs of individual works. Source and research material, notes, outlines, and production-related material, such as jacket copy and book jackets, can also be found. Corrected and multiple drafts, revealing the evolution of particular texts, are common for many titles.

Benét is well known for his long poem, John Brown's Body (1928), about the American Civil War, for which he was awarded a Pulitzer Prize in 1929, and for the short story, "The Devil and Daniel Webster" (1936), for which he was awarded the O. Henry Memorial Award for best American short story in 1937. Material can be found for these two popular works, as well as for longer works and collections, such as James Shore's Daughter (1934), Selected Works (1942), and the posthumous Western Star (1943). In addition to poetry and short stories, Benét also wrote book reviews, essays, forewords and introductions, radio plays, screenplays, and speeches.
Writings of Rosemary Benét include drafts and printed versions of poems, book reviews, essays, reader reports, and short stories.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series IV. Printed Appearances of Writings of Stephen Vincent Benét includes clippings of individual works, full issues of periodicals containing work(s) by Benét, and other printed versions of works.

There are examples of early work by Benét, written as an undergraduate while at Yale, but most of the work found here includes short forms published in popular American magazines and newspapers from the early 1920s until 1943. Types of work include poems, short stories, book reviews, profiles of authors, essays, and radio plays.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series V. contains clippings and printed ephemera relating to Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét. There are clippings of general interest relating to the Benéts, publicity and reviews relating to individual works by the Benéts, and periodicals and other ephemera acquired during their lifetime. Other ephemera includes such material as playbills (for stage performances), programs, T.V. guides, and ticket stubs.

arrangement.p: Organized into five subseries: Family Papers, Financial and Legal Records, Photographs, Rosemary Benét Material, and Other Papers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series VI. Personal Papers includes personal and family papers, financial and legal records, and photographs. The personal papers of Stephen Vincent and Rosemary Benét include calendars, diaries, notebooks, school records, and scrapbooks, as well as other material. Family papers denote material relating to other members of the Benét and Carr families. Financial and legal records include some publication-related records, such as contracts and royalty statements, as well as personal financial information.
